title: Stricter return-to-office rules fail to fill office spaces
description:
The anticipated remedy for deserted workplaces has yet to yield the expected results.

Organisations, eager to revive the pre-pandemic office culture, have recently enforced stricter return-to-office protocols. These include mandatory in-person attendance and reduced remote work flexibility. However, despite these efforts, a significant number of employees remain hesitant to return to their cubicles.

The ongoing uncertainty surrounding the pandemic, coupled with newfound preferences for remote work, has fostered resistance among the workforce. Employees cite health concerns, improved work-life balance, and increased productivity as reasons to continue remote work arrangements.

While employers argue that in-person collaboration fosters creativity and team cohesion, many staff members remain unconvinced. The dichotomy between management's desire for a bustling office and employees' preference for remote work continues to challenge the return-to-office narrative.

Businesses are now faced with the complex task of striking a balance between their return-to-office ambitions and the evolving desires of their workforce. The road ahead remains uncertain, as companies grapple with the persistent half-empty offices.

title: Historic U.S. House vote removes McCarthy from leadership
Facebook wants to charge a subscription fee
description: It's expected the company will begin charging $10 a month for the ad-free plan, which could begin within months.

title: Australian economy's recovery under threat amid global economic challenges
description:
These impediments, though seemingly minor individually, are collectively posing a significant risk to the nation's economic revival.

One such concern is the ongoing supply chain disruptions, largely attributed to the global shipping crisis. The delays in the movement of goods have resulted in increased costs and scarcity of essential supplies, affecting various industries and causing inflationary pressures.

Another 'paper cut' on Australia's recovery path is the uncertainty surrounding international travel. The country's reliance on tourism has been hampered by the sporadic opening and closing of borders due to the ongoing pandemic, leading to a lack of foreign visitors and dwindling revenues.

Furthermore, the housing market boom has led to concerns about a potential bubble, which, if burst, could have catastrophic consequences for the economy.

As Australia navigates through these intricate challenges, policymakers and businesses must tread cautiously to ensure a smoother path to recovery. Adapting to the changing global landscape and finding innovative solutions to these 'paper cuts' will be pivotal in securing a brighter economic future for the nation.

title: Historic U.S. House votes removes McCarthy from leadership
description:
The outcome of this unprecedented vote has the potential to reshape the political landscape within the House.

McCarthy, the House Minority Leader and prominent Republican figure, faces mounting pressure from members of his own party over his handling of critical issues and his allegiance to former President Donald Trump. This extraordinary vote comes as a culmination of internal strife within the Republican Party, with some members seeking a change in leadership direction.

The Republican Party is closely watching this vote, as it could have profound implications for the party’s future. If McCarthy is ousted from his leadership position, it may signal a shift in the party’s direction and its relationship with Trump’s influence.

As the vote proceeds, political analysts and pundits are scrutinising the proceedings, anticipating the results, and speculating about potential consequences. The eyes of the nation are fixed on this historic moment in American politics.

title: Why has the popular 30-year fixed mortgage in the U.S. risen to its highest level in nearly 23 years?
description:
U.S. mortgage rates surged to their highest level in nearly 23 years as inflation pressures persist.

The average rate on the popular 30-year fixed mortgage has risen to 7.72%.

Rates have not been this high since the end of 2000.

James Rodriguez, Senior Real Estate Reporter with Insider joins Veronica Dudo to discuss.

title: Can We Be Truly Sustainable
description: Australia's former Chief Scientist Professor Alan Finkel joins Tim Harcourt to discuss the status of Australia's plans to decarbonise, the opportunities that exist for new economic growth and ultimately answer the question, can we be truly sustainable.

title: Xi Jinping is taking over China's sharemarket
description:
Xi's government has unveiled a series of measures aimed at consolidating authority over the country's stock market, signalling a desire for greater economic stability and control.

The reforms include stricter regulations for listing on Chinese stock exchanges, with companies needing to meet more stringent criteria to go public. 

Additionally, the government is increasing its oversight of foreign listings by Chinese firms, a move seen as an attempt to prevent capital flight.

title: Investors worry as Tesla misses targets
description:
The EV giant's stock tumbled as investors expressed concerns over the company's ability to meet its ambitious growth targets.

In the third quarter of this year, Tesla delivered a total of 220,500 vehicles, missing Wall Street's estimates.

This disappointing performance raised doubts about the company's ability to keep up with the soaring demand for its EVs, especially as competitors continue to enter the market.

title: Did Sami Bankman-Fried offer money to stop Trump from running?
description:
It's been revealed that Sam Bankman-Fried, the CEO of FTX crypto exchange, explored the idea of offering former President Donald Trump a substantial sum of money to dissuade him from running for president again. 



The proposition is detailed in an upcoming book that promises to shed light on behind-the-scenes dealings and unconventional political strategies.

title: Australia's power network is facing a terrible summer
description:
The report, released by the Energy Authority of Australia, highlights that New South Wales, Queensland, and South Australia are at the greatest risk of experiencing blackouts. Increased demand for electricity due to air conditioning use during hot summer days is the primary driver of this concern.

The report suggests that immediate measures should be taken to mitigate these risks. These measures include improving grid infrastructure, investing in renewable energy sources, and implementing demand-side management programs to reduce peak electricity consumption.

Energy Minister Sarah Thompson acknowledged the challenges but assured the public that the government is actively working on solutions to prevent power shortages. She stated, "We are committed to ensuring a stable and reliable power supply during the summer months."

As the summer approaches, Australians will be closely monitoring the situation, hoping that the necessary steps will be taken to ensure a steady power supply during the hottest days.

title: Retro Atari 2600 revival: Plays your vintage cartridges
description:
The resurgence of this iconic gaming relic, with a headline that reads "A new Atari 2600 will play your old cartridges," has excited gamers of all ages.

Long-time fans and collectors can rejoice as they dust off their boxes of old game cartridges, as this new Atari console provides the opportunity to relive the golden era of gaming. Atari, the pioneering company behind the original 2600, has capitalised on the resurgence of retro gaming by creating a modern console with compatibility for the original cartridges.

This move has ignited a buzz in the gaming community, with enthusiasts eager to revisit timeless titles like "Pac-Man," "Space Invaders," and "Asteroids" on a faithful recreation of the classic hardware. The Atari 2600's simple yet addictive gameplay is expected to charm a new generation of gamers who crave the vintage gaming experience.

The release of this nostalgic console has left many wondering about the future of retro gaming and its potential impact on the modern gaming industry. Will it spark a resurgence of other classic consoles, and how will this affect the gaming market?

title: How the West can win the climate war
description:
Hosted by Professor Tim Harcourt of the University of Technology Sydney (UTS), the episode features an insightful interview with Professor Alan Finkel, the former Chief Scientist of Australia.

During the interview, Finkel expressed optimism about the feasibility of transitioning to clean energy. He highlighted the progress made in recent years, emphasizing that the transition might be happening more rapidly than many anticipate. Finkel acknowledged Australia's historical advantage in coal, iron ore, and LNG industries but cautioned against sudden shifts, advocating for a well-managed transition to minimize economic disruptions.

The discussion also delved into the international implications of Australia's clean energy transition, especially in the Indo-Pacific region. Finkel emphasized the importance of fostering positive trading relationships and partnerships with neighboring countries as Australia explores its clean energy export prospects.

Regarding the export potential of clean energy, Finkel encouraged exploring these opportunities as a potential replacement for revenues from coal, iron ore, and LNG in the future. He underscored the importance of economic incentives in driving behavioral changes as part of the great transformation, highlighting the role of science and policy in shaping our sustainable future.

In a world often inundated with discouraging environmental news, this episode of "The Great Transformation" offers a glimmer of hope, suggesting that with careful planning and international cooperation, a clean energy future is not only possible but also economically viable.

title: Biden blasts GOP over shutdown, calls for standalone Ukraine funding bill
description:
"I'm sick and tired of this political brinkmanship," Biden declared, as he urged Congress to pass a separate funding bill to support Ukraine.

The President argued that the ongoing dispute over government funding should not be tied to crucial aid for Ukraine, a country facing ongoing conflict and in desperate need of international support. Biden's call for a standalone Ukraine funding bill received mixed reactions from lawmakers on both sides of the aisle.

Republicans countered by highlighting concerns about the national debt and government spending. They argued that bundling Ukraine aid with the budget would ensure responsible fiscal management.

The deadlock in Congress continues, with the threat of a government shutdown looming as negotiations stall. As the political drama unfolds, the fate of Ukraine's much-needed assistance hangs in the balance.

title: Is the housing market surge a bubble waiting to burst?
description:
Despite the ongoing economic challenges, the real estate sector appears to be thriving, leaving experts and homeowners both astonished and hopeful.

Over the past year, the real estate landscape has been anything but predictable. 

But the surge in demand has been met with a limited supply of available homes. 

Builders have struggled to keep pace with the soaring demand, making the situation worse.

title: Cybersecurity experts on the best ways to protect your business
description:
Regulators around the world are stepping up scrutiny  of corporations who have failed to uphold proper cybersecurity protocols.

And on the eve of cybersecurity awareness month, experts are warning that it's important to get the basics right of protecting your customers - or your own data.

For more, we're joined by Annie Hagger of Cyber GC, and Sam Fariborz, group manager of cybersecurity services & program at the Kmart Group.

title: How will we invest in the future?
description: Tim Harcourt looks at the future of Investing in Australia and offshore with guests Amber Rabinov, AustralianSuper’s Head of Macro Research & Strategy and Lewis Apostolou partner and head of the Australia Funds Transactions Group at Baker McKenzie.

title: OpenAI’s ChatGPT can now see, hear, and speak
description:
OpenAI’s ChatGPT can now see, hear, and speak. 

The announcement comes as competitors are jumping into the ‘AI’ space. 

So, what impact will this have on the tech sector?

Oz Sultan, the Chief Strategist with the Sultan Interactive Group joins Veronica Dudo to discuss.

title: Pentagon plans vast  ‘AI’ fleet to counter threats from China
description:
The Pentagon intends to field a vast network of ‘AI’ powered technology, drones, and autonomous systems within the next two years to counter threats from China and other adversaries.

Oz Sultan, the Chief Strategist with the Sultan Interactive Group joins Veronica Dudo to discuss.

title: Did the U.S. just find the world's largest deposit of lithium?
description:
A lithium deposit discovered in a volcanic crater along the Nevada-Oregon border may hold up to 40 million metric tons of the rare metal — possibly the largest ever in the world.

Oz Sultan, the Chief Strategist with the Sultan Interactive Group joins Veronica Dudo to discuss.

title: British PM's new "proportionate" approach to climate policy
description:
British Prime Minister Rishi Sunak is set to unveil a more 'proportionate' and 'balanced' approach to tackling climate change. 

It comes amidst growing concerns over the economic implications of rapid climate policy changes and the need to strike a harmonious balance between environmental responsibility and economic stability.

title: Canada and India clash over assassination claims
description:
Trudeau announced that Canadian intelligence agencies were actively pursuing credible allegations tying New Delhi's agents to the shooting of Hardeep Singh Nijjar in British Columbia in June, in a rare such attack on the world's largest democracy.

Canadian and American authorities have initiated a close collaboration to investigate a possible connection between India and the assassination of Hardeep Singh Nijjar. 

The two nations are working in tandem to uncover any potential links that may shed light on the mysterious killing of Nijjar, a prominent figure in the Sikh community.

Hardeep Singh Nijjar, known for his activism and alleged connections to Sikh separatist groups, was found dead under suspicious circumstances in Canada. 

His death has raised concerns about potential foreign involvement, prompting Canada and the United States to intensify their efforts to unravel the truth.

The joint investigation is focusing on uncovering any evidence that could establish a connection between Nijjar's murder and entities in India.

Both countries are closely examining Nijjar's background, associations, and recent activities in an attempt to piece together the puzzle.

title: Is Qantas too close to the Government?
description:
A Senate inquiry in Australia has brought to light potential government support for the nation's flagship carrier, Qantas.

The inquiry, which aims to examine the aviation industry's ties with the government, revealed that Qantas does indeed appear to receive extra protection from government policies.

Among the findings was that airfares in Australia could have fallen by up to 10 per cent had the Government not blocked an appeal by Qatar Airways to add additional flights in Australia.

During the inquiry, several key figures in the aviation sector testified about the perceived advantages that Qantas enjoys.

These advantages reportedly include preferential treatment when it comes to landing rights, access to government contracts, and potential regulatory leniency.

While Qantas has denied receiving any special favours, the inquiry has raised questions about the level of government intervention in the aviation industry. 

Critics argue that such support, if proven, could stifle competition and harm smaller airlines struggling to survive.

title: U.S. prisoners freed from Iran make emotional return home after swap deal
description:
The emotional homecoming marked the end of a harrowing ordeal that had kept them separated from their loved ones for far too long.

The prisoners, who had been held in Iran on various charges, were exchanged for Iranian detainees in the United States, signalling a diplomatic breakthrough between the two nations.

Tearful embraces and joyful reunions unfolded as the former detainees stepped onto American soil, greeted by tearful family members and well-wishers.

The swap deal, brokered through intense diplomatic negotiations, has raised hopes for improved relations between the United States and Iran. 

Both nations have expressed their commitment to continuing dialogue and working towards a more peaceful future.

title: Why is the OECD predicting global economic slowdown?
description:
The body cites supply chain disruptions, rising inflation, and ongoing uncertainties related to the COVID-19 pandemic, as key drivers to this poor outlook.

Advanced economies, including the United States and the European Union and Australia, are expected to face the brunt of this deceleration, but emerging economies are set to grapple with their own set of challenges.

title: How can AI be made to sound more human?
description:
Many of us have taken to ChatGPT as if it's the second coming.

But while it's made our lives easier, sometimes the generative text isn't quite right or comes across as robotic and generic.

This can make writing sound stilted, and as user’s literacy in how the technology continues to evolve, a growing number of people are able to spot the use of generative AI a mile away.

So how can we make it better?

Devan Leos is the CCO and Co-founder of Undetectable AI, a proactive AI startup that's soared in popularity. 

The Undetectable AI tool rewrites ChatGPT or AI generated text content to make it identical to human writing, and therefore unable to be detected.

“We wanted to focus on creating a product that humanises artificial intelligence text content,” said Leos in an interview with Ticker. 

“There are certain identifiers that are blatantly ChatGPT,” he added, “it doesn’t really have a human feel to it.”

title: U.S. national debt just surpassed $33 trillion for the first time
description:
The national debt of the U.S. has surpassed $33 trillion for the first time.

The historic milestone comes less than two weeks before the federal government faces a potential shutdown over a lack of funding authorization.

Phillip Toews the CEO Toews Asset Management joins Veronica Dudo to discuss.

title: Is the U.S. Federal Reserve done raising rates?
description:
The major focus of stock market investors will be on the Federal Reserve's interest rate policy meeting. 

So, will the U.S. central bank hold interest rates steady after a stronger-than- expected inflation data for August?

Phillip Toews, the CEO Toews Asset Management joins Veronica Dudo to discuss.

title: Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi Heads to Russia
description:
The diplomatic mission comes at a time of increased global uncertainty, with both China and Russia facing challenges from Western powers.

Wang Yi's visit underscores the enduring partnership between China and Russia, as both nations seek to bolster their strategic ties. The talks are expected to cover a wide range of topics, including military cooperation, economic partnerships, and coordination on international issues.

One key focus of the discussions will likely be the evolving security situation in Asia and Europe. China and Russia share common concerns about the expansion of NATO and the United States' military presence in the Asia-Pacific region. They are expected to explore ways to counterbalance these developments and safeguard their respective interests.

title: Katy Perry sells album rights to Litmus Music for $225M
description:
The move signals a significant shift in the music industry's dynamics and could pave the way for other artists to explore similar opportunities.

Perry, known for chart-toppers like "Teenage Dream" and "Firework," has been a household name in the music world for over a decade. With this deal, she joins a growing list of artists who have opted to monetize their music catalogs in an evolving industry landscape.

Litmus Music, a heavyweight in the music investment sector, is set to gain access to Perry's extensive catalog, which includes hit albums like "One of the Boys" and "Prism." This acquisition not only secures them rights to her music but also opens up new avenues for remixes, licensing, and collaborations with other artists.

The $225 million deal underscores the increasing value of music catalogs in today's digital age, where streaming platforms have become the primary mode of music consumption. As artists explore innovative ways to capitalize on their work, investment firms like Litmus Music are strategically positioning themselves to acquire and profit from these assets.
